LYMPHOCYTIC CHORIOEMENINGITIS VIRUS - AUSTRALIA: (QUEENSLAND)
*************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 6 Sep 2021
Source: Dr Alyssa Pyke
<Alyssa.Pyke@health.qld.gov.au>


The Public Health Virology laboratory (PHV), Forensic and Scientific Services, Queensland Health have reported the isolation of the rodent-borne arenavirus, lymphocytic choriomeningitis virus (LCMV), from products of conception tissue taken from a 28-year-old woman, residing in southern Queensland (QLD). The patient miscarried in July 2021 in the setting of a febrile illness with associated headaches. Laboratory diagnostics detected anti-LCMV IgM and IgG antibodies in the patient's serum using immunofluorescent assays prior to the miscarriage. LCMV RNA was detected in the products of conception tissue by RT-PCR [1] and the same sample yielded an LCMV isolate in 4 vertebrate cell lines, including Vero E6 cells.

This case follows the recent diagnosis of LCMV infections by PHV since January 2021 in 13 other patients, all of whom resided in the same region in southern QLD as the above patient. Metagenomic sequencing and phylogenetic analysis demonstrated LCMV sequences from the tissue isolate in July, as well as a CSF sample from one of the aseptic meningitis cases in January 2021, clustered phylogenetically together within genotype I.

Originally isolated in 1933 in the USA, LCMV is the prototype of the virus family _Arenaviridae_, consisting of enveloped viruses with bi-segmented RNA genomes. The house mouse, _Mus musculus_ is the primary reservoir host for LCMV and humans can be incidentally infected following exposure to urine, faeces or saliva from infected rodents or other fomites they have contaminated [2, 3]. Whilst most human LCMV infections are asymptomatic or result in a mild febrile illness, more serious clinical sequelae can develop, including aseptic meningitis or encephalitis. Vertical transmission of LCMV from infected pregnant women to their unborn fetus can result in miscarriage and fetal death. Human-to-human LCMV transmission associated with organ transplantation has also been documented [3].

A current mouse plague in Australia, likely precipitated by over-abundance of food following bountiful rainfall during the summer, has been particularly prevalent in New South Wales (NSW) and southern QLD regions during 2020-2021. In March 2021, a farmer from NSW was also diagnosed with an LCMV infection during the current mouse plague which has been implicated as the likely cause of the recently reported LCMV infections in both states [4]. Previously unrecognized in southern QLD, the recent LCMV infections described in this report highlight public health concerns that the geographical distribution of LCMV, and heightened risk of infection amid the current mouse plague, is more widespread, and not limited to the regions where locally acquired cases have occurred. Greater awareness of this current Australian viral threat and consideration of LCMV infection in mouse-infested areas should be a public health priority.

